#---------Chapter 4-----------
x86 Assembly and C
<<objdump>> entensively to read x86 assembly code.

$ objdump -d hello
It has many flags which is useful to learn. $ objdump -S hello | less and so on;

The assembly instructions has the following format:
The first column is an address of assembly instructions
The second column is the assembly instruction in hex values
The third column is the assembly instruciton. 
The optional fourth column is a comment appears when there is a reference to an address. 



Anatomy of an Assembly Instruction
----------------------------------

Anatomy of a Program
--------------------
Every program consists of code and data, and only those two components made up a program.
When a source file is compiled, the generated machine code is stored into an object file, which is just a block of binary.  One or more object files can be combined to produce an executable binary, which is complete program runnable in an operating system.
Each object file or executable binaries has an ELF binary;


<<readelf>> is a program that recognizes and displays the ELF metadata of a binary file, be itan object file or an executable binary. ELF - Executable and Linkable Format, is the content at the very beginning of an executable to provide an operating system necessary information to load into main memory and run the executable.


$ readelf -g a.out # it shows the ELF Header info


An ELF binary is composed of:
  - An ELF header: the very first section of an executable that describes the file's organization.
  - A program header table: is an array of fixed-size structures that describes segments of an executable.
  - A section header table: is an array of fixed-size structures that describes sections of an executable.
  - Segments and sections are the main content of an ELF binary, which are the code and data, divided into chunks of different purposes.
  




  
  --------------------
  ELF Header
  --------------------
  Program header table
  --------------------
  .text
  --------------------
  .rodata
  --------------------
  ...
  --------------------
  .data
  --------------------
